      <hedline>
        <hl1>Clutter as Inspiration</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nelson Marans letter found August 27 article on messy-desk syndrome amusing (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read with amusement the examples of the messy-desk syndrome (''At the Office, My Cluttered Desk Is My Castle,'' On the Job, Aug. 27).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read with amusement the examples of the messy-desk syndrome (''At the Office, My Cluttered Desk Is My Castle,'' On the Job, Aug. 27).</p>
        <p>For years as a chemist at a major corporation, I was noted for the piles of papers on my desk, on the floor, on  top of file cabinets and anywhere else space was available. But I could always find any required item within a reasonable time.</p>
        <p>After 20 years, a new president arrived, accompanied by an edict that only three items could be on a desk: an appointment calendar, a box for mail and a writing tablet. No exceptions were permitted.</p>
        <p>Unfortunately, during the neat-desk era, research productivity decreased markedly. A correlation? I would hope so!</p>
        <p>NELSON MARANS  Silver Spring, Md., Aug. 28</p>
      </block>
